"Morley N.J.","Thermodynamics of cercarial survival and metabolism in a changing climate",2011,"Parasitology","138","11",,"1442","1452",,,10.1017/S0031182011001272,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80053078970&partnerID=40&md5=43b9fb97ef237d499d88e87848263478","School of Biological Sciences, Royal Holloway, University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom","Morley, N.J., School of Biological Sciences, Royal Holloway, University of London, Egham, Surrey TW20 0EX, United Kingdom","Cercariae are non-feeding free-living stages in the life cycles of trematodes, highly influenced by temperature. Their life span is brief, limited by the depletion of a non-renewable glycogen store. Warmer temperatures under the influence of climate change may promote the transmission of parasites and therefore understanding their thermobiology forms an important step in discerning the future dynamics of parasite populations. An empirical relationship exists between cercarial mean expected life span and the half-life of the population (t0A.5) and therefore t0A.5 is a good indicator of glycogen utilization. In this study experimental data on the effects of temperature on cercarial survival is compiled from the scientific literature and evaluated in terms of metabolism using Q10 and Arrhenius activation energy (E* or μ), common measures of temperature-mediated reaction rates. Cercariae have a variable response to temperature, which does not appear to be influenced by their life-history attributes or size. There were little differences in Q10 and E* values between most temperature ranges. In almost half the studies examined (7 of 16) cercariae demonstrated a discrete zone of thermostability over a range equivalent to typical individual mean summer temperatures. Distinct intraspecific differences in temperature responses between 3 laboratory strains of Schistosoma mansoni and 2 natural strains of Echinoparyphium recurvatum sensu stricto were apparent. The importance of these results for cercarial biology under global climate change is discussed. © Copyright Cambridge University Press 2011.","Cercariae; Climate change; Metabolism; Survival; Temperature; Trematodes","glycogen; article; cercaria; climate change; global change; host parasite interaction; life cycle; metabolism; nonhuman; parasite survival; priority journal; Schistosoma mansoni; summer; temperature; temperature dependence; thermodynamics; thermostability; Animals; Cercaria; Climate; Climate Change; Ecosystem; Fishes; Glycogen; Half-Life; Life Cycle Stages; Longevity; Mammals; Mollusca; Population Dynamics; Seasons; Temperature; Thermodynamics; Trematoda; Trematode Infections; Echinoparyphium recurvatum; Schistosoma mansoni; Trematoda",,"glycogen, 9005-79-2; Glycogen, 9005-79-2",,,,"Atkinson, D., Temperature and organism size - A biological law for ectotherms? (1994) ADV.ECOL.RES., 25, pp. 1-58; Brandts, J.F., Heat effects on proteins and enzymes (1967) Thermobiology, pp. 25-72. , Academic Press, London, UK, (ed. Rose, A. H.); Combes, C., Theron, A., Les densites cercariennes (1981) Memoires du Museum National D'Histoire Naturelle, Serie A, Zoologie, 119, pp. 186-196; Crozier, W.J., On biological oxidations as function of temperature (1924) Journal of General Physiology, 7, pp. 189-216; Evans, N.A., The influence of environmental temperature upon transmission of the cercariae of Echinostoma liei ( Digenea: Echinostomatidae). (1985) Parasitology, 90 (2), pp. 269-275; Evans, N.A., Gordon, D.M., Experimental studies on the transmission dynamics of the cercariae of Echinoparyphium recurvatum ( Digenea: Echinostomatidae) (1983) Parasitology, 87 (1), pp. 167-174; Gammermaister, T.P., Materials on the heat resistance of cercariae of some species of trematodes (Russian) (1977) Parazitologiya, 11 (1), pp. 24-28; Ginetsinskaya, T.A., The relationship between the distribution of glycogen in the bodies of different cercariae and their biological peculiarities (1960) Doklady Bio